@Steven M. 

Snowdrops (one word)  are flowering plants.

They flower from January to March, so you know springtime is around the corner.

@Mean Old Lady

I read "Whose Body," a while back and if I knew that then I've forgotten, but I've always meant to read more of the series, so this is a good reminder!

After all, HOW could a mere mortal commoner, such as myself, resist a lord propelling a PUNT with a long pole in manly fashion!?

@Evan 
That was my final hurdle!  I had WOW for the expression of shock (which of course was a mess_ ) and then when I got that straight, HIGH STORY....STORIE....  that damned 56D...

Finally got it, with my teeth gritted....

@Ken
What a nice way to say it! You might have put your finger on the sweet spot for those who sometimes complain about the difficulty level. (I happen to like impossibly deceitful, but that’s just me.)

Thanks for the apt description!

@Mean Old Lady 
I believe the North Shore’s world fame is due to the giant waves for surfing found there.  



Long Island has a North Shore, too, emus, but that didn't fit.

@Hardroch 

I encountered that sense of CAP in some earlier puzzle (New Yorker, maybe?), but it didn’t stick. Maybe this time? And I think you’re right that it comes from African-American Vernacular English.

For whatever reason, a percent symbol in a URL will break the link in these comments. I learned from another commenter that URL shorteners can sidestep that. (I use <a href="https://tinyurl.com/app" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/app</a>.)

@Hardroch 

I got CAP completely on crosses and kind of forgot about it in the midst of all the other fun answers but I have never heard of it before in that context... At least not to my recollection. 

Thanks for providing some possible background on it!

@Judith Fairview so agree
Had a few lookups but trivia kept at minimum. Great word play.
First Fri in ages I enjoyed.
